      <item>
        <title>Fleeting Glimpse</title>
        <author>hello@minutestomidnight.co.uk (Simone Silvestroni)</author>
        <description><![CDATA[
          It'll be a while until I can be able to find any meaningful words to describe my 2025 Christmas.
          <p>I’ve been living away from my hometown since 1996, which is when I started deluding myself with a now pointless certainty: the idea that distance would help my innate inability to accept things that end, people who die, and everything around it.</p>

<p>I lost my beloved mother on the 25th, a thousand kilometres away from where I stood still during a devastating phone call. Standing there, listening to my dear dad screaming in desperation, while his spouse and companion of 61 years was leaving him — and us — in real time. I waited on the line, crying, while paramedics arrived, tried something, and eventually picked up the phone to let me know that “the lady has died peacefully on the couch, in her home”. I know he was trying to say something comforting, a futile attempt to bring a sort of “kind rationality” to something that was actually a torment burrowing its way through my body and mind.</p>

<p>One day, I might be able to talk about what happened, and what’s happening. Today is not that day. I just feel the absence like a scorching absurdity, as painful as it can be. The past is slipping away, with time showing its harsh relentless truth: how a life, as important as it can be for an entire family, is a fleeting glimpse. You can turn around, warm your bones in front of a fire in a cozy room, and suddenly it is no more.</p>

          <hr /><p><a href="mailto:hello@minutestomidnight.co.uk?subject=Fleeting%20Glimpse">Reply via email</a></p>]]>
        </description>
        <pubDate>Wed, 31 Dec 2025 20:03:21 +0000</pubDate>
