      <item>
        <title>More About Noise</title>
        <author>hello@minutestomidnight.co.uk (Simone Silvestroni)</author>
        <description><![CDATA[
          My <a href='/noise/'>latest post</a> generated an unusual amount of email exchanges. The back-and-forth was fantastic, rich, and inspiring, pushing me to contemplate more ways in which noise affects me these days.
          <p>One letter, in particular, picked my curiosity. Wrote <a href="https://meanwhiling.com/">by Noa</a>, its overture was:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>I’m a fairly long term reader of your blog. I wanted to reach out because your recent post “noise” really resonated with me.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>The thing about being a “long term reader” kind of stunned me. I’m fairly convinced that the people who read my ramblings are the ones that I know already. My pen pals of sorts, people that I’m used to exchange emails with. I guess the independent small web still manages to surprise.</p>

<p>Is this what happens when you ditch the corporate ultra-capitalist web paraphernalia? When you drop the pretence, renounce to vanity numbers, data, online performance, self-brand, projected persona?</p>

<p>It also made me wonder: how many people have I been reading for years without ever making an attempt to get in touch privately?</p>

<p>Back to the letter. We got to talk about <em>the noise</em>, until I came up with an analogy that might explain how I perceive social media today:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Imagine you are in a lovely cafe, with a back garden and all. Very relaxing. Sipping some amazing beverage, having tasty pastries, while having a relaxing conversation with a close friend, or your spouse. Imagine that your conversation gets suddenly interrupted by someone you barely know, or maybe even a stranger out of the blue. They pick up a chair, join you at the table, immediately starting to throw unsolicited comments.<br /><br />
Then, as quickly as they have arrived, they leave. Someone else appears, repeating the pattern. At some point, you realise you’ve been there for an hour, half-replied to dozens of people who are not close friends of yours, and don’t really know you intimately. You notice how all this completely derailed your original private conversation.<br /><br />
You don’t even remember what happened, or where and how it started, ending up with a bunch of scattered thoughts by someone you might not see ever again. Maybe some nice idea here and there, but definitely not a deep conversation. You’re not really enriched, and you wasted time that you could have used differently.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>I realised that Noa is indeed a stranger to me, and yet, I was having a much deeper conversation than I could have had on Mastodon, or any other part of whatever can be considered a <em>social network</em>. I’m not against meeting new people virtually — quite the contrary. I just had yet another proof.</p>

<p>Noa also wrote:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Short-form social media encourages speed, but speed discourages depth. The trouble is that most social media websites that supported long form content have either disappeared, or buried that functionality behind layers of distraction and unneeded features.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Speed. I had not thought about it. I keep thinking about asynchronous communication, old tech from the Nineties, and never realised that one common factor was a lack of speed. Things were happening at a pace that felt human. Speed also discourages focus, which brings me to another observation.</p>

<h2 id="ipod">iPod</h2>

<p>An article from the culture section of a newspaper (luckily they offer an RSS feed for each section) made me want to look for the iPod ads of the early 2000s. Of course, I found a supercut containing them all.</p>

<p>Some twenty-five minutes later, one thing stood out. All the ads for any subsequent model of iPod clearly showed a prominent feature: people who were hyper focused on the music. They were <em>lost in it</em>. Dancing, jumping, moving around with their white-corded earphones.</p>

<p>Until the iPod Touch came around.</p>

<p>Then, it swiftly changed to people playing video games, messaging, looking at websites, watching TV shows, using the iPod for anything <em>except</em> for losing themselves in one focused activity. The era of constant distractions. The uninspiring black slab. They can add any colour they like, it’ll remain a metal-plastic-glass dead slab built for distraction.</p>

<p>Enjoy a gem from a bygone era:</p>

<div class="iframe-container fullscreen">
	<iframe title="Winton Marsalis for iPod" src="https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/2GvGc1Oec6U" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" loading="lazy" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscreen="">
	</iframe>
</div>

