      <item>
        <title>Trip to Somewhere</title>
        <author>hello@minutestomidnight.co.uk (Simone Silvestroni)</author>
        <description><![CDATA[
          Twenty-one years ago, I received a phone call whilst sleeping. Someone close to me had passed away, two days after I last saw him in the hospital. I knew it would have been our last goodbye when I left the ward. Ignoring anyone else who could see me, I cried in the street of Milan.
          <p>After the phone call, I stayed with his father, accompanying him at every stage while trying to help as much as I could during the ordeal. The trauma of losing someone my age two years earlier, taught me the powerful violence of enduring such a pain. I saw how parents should not be forced to bury their children, and yet, it was the second time in two years for me to witness.</p>

<p>We went together to attend the grim requirements of bureaucracy, and was there with him when we collected the urn. Sitting in the back of a car for two-hundred miles, I kept the remains very close, protected by my coat, as if the warmth could bring some comfort.</p>

<p>That car brought us from Milan to our tiny hometown on the seaside. There, he would rest forever, while his father could finally retire. I watched him during that trip, barely saying a word, welling up throughout without ever letting himself go. I knew him very well, he would have needed to be alone. Pain was a private thing, and I understood.</p>

<p>He had made a few mistakes in his prime, spent the rest of his life trying to fix them, devoted to save the son that was in the urn next to me. Too late.</p>

<p>I watched him trudging through the hometown for a couple days. At the cemetery, he didn’t say a word, watching the urn as it was set to rest next to my grandparents, on a cold sunny day in February. I watched him, an utterly defeated man.</p>

<p>After spending his whole adult life in the big city, he indeed retired in our hometown. His old plan of sharing his autumn years together with his only son didn’t materialise. Too late.</p>

<p>Two decades, slowly drifting between memories, photographs, books to read, films to watch. We kept exchanging lots of emails during these years, opening up to each other. Including talking about the painful process of loss, how we grieve.</p>

<p>Since he was a technophobe, constantly afraid of losing data, he had a maniacal relathionship with his printer. My first blog, the one I had started in 2002 and subsequently erased from my computers and from the Wayback machine, it turned out he had it. Printed, in full.</p>

<p>We kept writing emails, until he couldn’t remember how to use a computer. A strange form of dementia caught up with him a couple years ago — I say ‘strange’ because he never forgot our names, who we were, our roles in the various stages of his life. In one of his last letters, he explained how he felt: like he was “already dead”.</p>

<p>A month ago, I received a call whilst sleeping. He passed away. My dear uncle, defeated by his one attempt at life, who tried his best no matter what.</p>

<p>I stayed a week there, helping my family with the grim requirements of bureaucracy. This time, my sister got to protect and keep his urn warm before setting him to rest.</p>

<p>I went through his things, sorted documents, papers, things to keep and things to destroy. Among a dozen big folders, mostly packed with bills, I noticed a red one. My name was on a label placed on the edge. Inside, our emails, printed.</p>

<p>Despite having all those letters in my computer, I spent many hours reading them. Printed on paper, they felt different, a proper labour of love.</p>

<p>Safe travels, uncle A.</p>

          <hr /><p><a href="mailto:hello@minutestomidnight.co.uk?subject=Trip%20to%20Somewhere">Reply via email</a></p>]]>
        </description>
