      <item>
        <title>Riding the Wave</title>
        <author>hello@minutestomidnight.co.uk (Simone Silvestroni)</author>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/assets/images/mavericks_settings.webp" alt="Screenshot of Mac OS X Mavericks showing Desktop, Dock, and the System Preferences window" />
          Semi-random notes on my ongoing experience of living in the (tech) past.
          <p>After taking the plunge, Mavericks keeps on giving. I created a brand new <a href="https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/setup/">Set-up page</a> featuring a probably incomplete list of everything I’m using. I’ll be adding more info along the way, and probably more pictures.</p>

<h2 id="experience-notes">Experience Notes</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Mavericks’ Aqua GUI, with its elegant and refined animations, gives a feeling that everything is running exceptionally well together. Almost as if it was a well-thought and organic piece of software (imagine that!).</li>
  <li>I never have to take breaks because of eye fatigue.</li>
  <li>Never felt a need to enable accessibility features to increase contrast or similar. The reason is that the Aqua GUI is already designed to have the correct depth, texture and contrast. Probably because its lead designer was catering for real people.</li>
  <li>Mavericks is definitely faster, easier and more intuitive to use.</li>
  <li>The Settings app (System Preferences) is a proper computer control panel. I know where every single item, or sub-item, is, as opposed to the horribly clunky iOS-like vertical version Apple have imposed from macOS Ventura.</li>
  <li>Older software is more efficient and quicker, despite running on a computer that’s more than 12 years old. Basically, it’s bug-free compared to their recent versions. Bloat-free software is the best.</li>
  <li>The same tasks on this computer take considerably less time. One extreme case study: last time I had to reinstall my dev environment using homebrew on the ‘modern’ MacBook Pro required more than 3 hours. MacPorts in Mavericks took less than 5 minutes to set everything up and be up and running.</li>
  <li>Most old software that is now abandonware is either on-par or superior to later incarnations. See Logic Studio or Adobe, among others.</li>
  <li>The result is less stress, and more time that I can spend on the computer without needing constant breaks, or swearing.</li>
  <li>A note on the above point: stress is very important, I’ve been way more calm after I switched to Mavericks than I’ve been in years (while working on a tech device).</li>
  <li>I don’t miss dark mode at all, on the contrary. My hypothesis is that dark mode was made necessary by the ‘blinding’ nature of the newer flat OSes.</li>
</ul>

          <hr /><p><a href="mailto:hello@minutestomidnight.co.uk?subject=Riding%20the%20Wave">Reply via email</a></p>]]>
        </description>
        <pubDate>Sun, 28 Sep 2025 11:44:57 +0100</pubDate>
