      <item>
        <title>Production, mix, master: &apos;Alien Pop&apos;</title>
        <author>hello@minutestomidnight.co.uk (Simone Silvestroni)</author>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/assets/images/alien_pop_cover.webp" alt="Cover for the album 'Alien Pop'" />
          I co-produced, mixed and mastered Rythur's debut album. He's a friend from the US, currently living in Colorado.
          <div class="iframe-bandcamp">
	<iframe style="border: 0; width: 100%; height: 350px;" src="https://bandcamp.com/EmbeddedPlayer/album=2646258534/size=large/bgcol=333333/linkcol=e99708/artwork=small/transparent=true/" seamless=""><a href="https://rythur.bandcamp.com/album/alien-pop">Alien Pop, by Rythur</a></iframe>
</div>

<h2 id="todays-the-day">Today’s the day</h2>

<p>I met <a href="https://rythur.bandcamp.com/">Rythur</a> online on <a href="https://mastodon.social/@rythur">the fediverse</a> some time ago, where we quickly bonded. His awesomely quirky (to me) approach to songwriting has always been a source of keen curiosity.</p>

<p>When I heard the demos a defined thought formed: “this could become a great work with the right producer”. I’m not sure if I was the right-est, but it felt good. And while it <a href="https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/acceptance/">took me way too long</a>, to complete my work, the important thing is that today’s the day.</p>

<p>From the album liners, one of the best compliments I’ve ever received:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>I needed a FRIEND who actually liked my music and could master it well.</p>

  <p>I could tell, from previous conversations with Simone, that he was exactly the right person for my sounds. I had heard Simone’s Minutes to Midnight project and was blown away by the substance and clarity of it all. I knew from this that he knew how to shape sounds around themes and messages. <cite>Rythur</cite></p>
</blockquote>

<h2 id="production-notes">Production Notes</h2>

<p>Similarly to my <a href="https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/la-matiere-meme-du-temps/">last music production</a>, the workflow with Ryan was pretty different from my usual. I’m used to receive source files in either Logic or Pro Tools, or sometimes stereo multitracks. While ẓavajêr sent me Audacity self-contained projects, Ryan provided songs in Garage Band. My optimism about Garage Band was quickly stifled when I saw how Logic crashed on every song import. For whatever reason, a different version of Logic, installed on a test machine running another macOS, opened 3 tracks out of 6, keeping its crash routine on the other half. I’m talking about the most recent versions here.</p>

<p>I changed strategy. Installed Garage Band, edited a few things directly in there, and exported each track as a proper audio file, recreating Logic sessions from scratch and importing said tracks. At that stage, it was a matter of getting into the feeling of the ‘themes and messages’ that Ryan mentioned in his liners.</p>

<p>One thing that I noticed, production-wise, was my instinct towards a total respect for certain sounds. In the past, I would have engaged with the artist, proposing slight changes and alterations, new sound banks for this or that instrument. Nothing major, but enough to slightly alter the overall texture of certain sections. Of course, the artist would have to agree, and generally speaking they did, because my intent was always to improve the overall impact of the message.</p>

<p>Not this time. It struck me how, after an initial tentative drum replacement, the general feeling was lost. I went another way: kept the intricacies of the sound textures together, left all the original instruments intact, limited my interventions to refining and polishing. A lot of EQ, compression, riding the gain, curating the sound image, and finding the sweet spot between drums and bass.</p>

<p>In the end, I didn’t overdo things, I used the essential tools at my disposal, creating personal presets that I could reuse across songs for specific instruments, to keep the overall style consistent. Cohesion was my end goal.</p>

<h3 id="bass">Bass</h3>

<p>After a first run of mixes was delivered, I got to engage with Ryan’s comments, requests for changes and so on. One day something happened. During a session of fixes for <em>I Wanna Knw</em>, I felt this unique urge to pick up my bass and replace the existing track with something deeper. While I largely respected the original part, I’ve added some personal flare, a different texture, little movements that are impossible to reproduce with a keyboard and a sampler. I was mesmerised, with a result so good that it only required two takes.</p>

<p>There was something sensual in the song, this non-dialogue between two distant people, this relationship that’s alive and dead at the same time, with burning embers clearly there. It’s the doubt of the narrator, the duality of their messaging each other, that pushed me to add a real deep bass sound to the song. To me, it needed that, something that makes the legs tremble.</p>

<h3 id="daws">DAWs</h3>

<p>I used Logic to mix the whole album. Throughout the production, I kept having this nagging feeling that I was doing “too little”, that I wasn’t giving the project my whole professional self. In reality, the realisation came at the very end, I was only keeping the initial inner promise: leave the core of his music intact. Ryan’s style is so peculiar, personal, the brainchild of someone with a life very different from mine, and yet, so very close.</p>

<p>For my pre-master stage, I switched to Reaper, re-familiarised with it after a long stint away from the software. Finally, I ended up mastering in WaveLab. Even though initially I didn’t want to, I felt like its environment invited me not to be distracted by further potential tinkering with the mix. Ended up doing way more polishing in WaveLab than anticipated, probably because I let too much time pass between sessions.</p>

<p>I’m quite happy with the result. It was not a familiar process for me, but once again, it’s when I move away from my comfort zone that I find ways to explore new things, allowing interesting and fun ideas to bloom.</p>

<h2 id="credits">Credits</h2>

<h3 id="performed-by">Performed by</h3>

<dl>
  <dt>Dr. Ryan Matthew Thurman</dt>
  <dd>all instrumentation and vocals</dd>
  <dt>Simone Silvestroni</dt>
  <dd>bass in ‘I Wanna Knw’</dd>
</dl>

<h3 id="visual-media">Visual Media</h3>

<p><a href="http://sandralisidesign.com/">Sandra Lisi</a>.</p>

