      <item>
        <title>Getting Ready for the Winter. Part 1, Switching Technology</title>
        <author>hello@minutestomidnight.co.uk (Simone Silvestroni)</author>
        <description><![CDATA[
          First of a short series of posts, where I introduce my switch to an operating system released in 2013, running in a computer built the same year. I can't possibly explain all the fine details of how it works, it'd require a book, but I'll try to dig out the best impressions.
          <p>As explained at <a href="https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/looking-for-a-niche/">the end of July</a>, I found myself at the bitter end of a long process of detaching from modern computing. Apple in particular. As a pure experiment, I installed and ran Mac OS X 10.9.5 (nicknamed ‘Mavericks’) on an old MacBook Air. I liked it a lot. Way more than I had initially anticipated.</p>

<h2 id="back-to-the-past">Back to the Past</h2>

<p>Fixated with wanting to prove the folly of craving the latest shiny thing, I thought a good attempt would be to record and produce a single song using tech considered obsolete by today’s standards. Instead, something unexpected happened.</p>

<p>As I was increasingly noticing the ease of use, how the UI agreed with me, how fun and smooth using Mavericks was, I progressively started to flirt with the idea of switching completely to it.</p>

<p>So I did it.</p>

<p>Went to eBay to purchase a near-mint 2013 MacBook Pro, with great specs and a brand new battery. Price was less than a cheap Android phone.</p>

<p>Taking the plunge was less scary than I thought. Riding the wave (Mavericks pun intended) was exciting, as well as challenging at times, bringing an inexplicable feeling of accomplishment once I reached the final realisation: I could seriously replace every single software with either an older release, or something that I had abandoned long ago. Or, in some cases, with the latest modern version (Firefox, Chromium, Reaper, among these), because there is people working to maintain software for older OSes, bless them.</p>

<h2 id="abandonware">Abandonware</h2>

<p>To effectively go live in a tech past, a key concept had to be tattooed in my brain. I wrote this in my above linked ‘niche’ post:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>What has the Mavericks experiment showed me? That I grew up in a world where designers cared about their work, and also about the people who would end up using such work. Also, it demonstrated, in a direct and somehow brutal way, how every single so-called improvement that came later was mostly redundant, likely a marketing gimmick forced to sell more crap.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Once realised how most modern software has been constantly and hastily updated not for the sake of progress, but rather to follow a cycle of planned obsolescence, everything started to fall into place.</p>

<p>I couldn’t believe until I tried. I made a list of every app from my modern computing setups, looked for their last version supported in Mavericks (often carrying a <em>de facto</em> status of “abandonware”), and installed it. The vast majority is unbelieavably better: more usable, fast, better performant, mostly bug-free.</p>

<p>What do these older versions have in common?</p>

<ul>
  <li>No bloat.</li>
  <li>No marketing lingo and no patronising: you won’t find “maybe later” as an alternative to “yes”.</li>
  <li>Awesomely intuitive user interface.</li>
  <li>A beautiful icon that doesn’t look like it was designed by a 5-year-old child.</li>
  <li>Apple wasn’t trying to force me into doing what they wanted me to do, which leads to the refreshing and long forgotten feeling of actually owning my computer, which ultimately leads to my last point:</li>
  <li>Exceptional user experience.</li>
</ul>

<p>Again and again, I’ve been struck by surprise for how better the older incarnations of my software roster are, to the point where using their up to date versions on modern Macs feels now utterly frustrating.</p>

<p>Random examples: Carbon Copy Cloner, iA Writer, Apple Mail (this one really left me speechless, I had stopped using Apple Mail years ago), Lossless Cut, everything from Adobe.</p>

<p>The concept of abandonware is an unending fascination: a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abandonware">seemingly grey area</a> where the legality of using it remains entirely unclear in practical terms (law says something different). Versions that are considered obsolete by the software company, unsupported, in many cases removed from their website.</p>

<p>Things like Adobe Creative Suite 3, 4 or 5, or Logic Pro 9 with its attached suite of ‘Pro Audio apps’, Apple Aperture, Final Cut Pro 7, Sketch 3, iWork ‘09. I have the whole lot, mostly because I had purchased them many years ago. Had I not owned them, they could have been found on either <a href="https://macintoshgarden.org/">The Macintosh Garden</a> or <a href="https://www.macintoshrepository.org/">The Macintosh Repository</a>.</p>

<p>Quick note about Adobe: I don’t give a flying flamingo that the company unilaterally decided to shut down their activation servers for old versions. Their obsolescence game is for them, I’m perfectly content with reinstalling the software and authorise it with “alternative” methods. I paid for that shit, so that shit is mine, Jack.</p>

<p>Then, one unexpected surprise: software companies let me download old versions from their servers, often not exposed to the public. Some of them really went above their remit to help me out. More about this later.</p>

<p>These old programs work flawlessly, by the way — with or without an internet connection.</p>

<h3 id="example-ia-writer">Example: iA Writer</h3>

<p>I’m cronically unable to use modern iA Writer. Have been experiencing bugs on top of bugs, crashes, tickets with their helpdesk to little avail. All because of the “Library” functionality. Eventually, I switched to other Markdown editors, without ever finding a satisfactory replacement.</p>

<p>The Library functionality reminded me of how much I dislike software with a tendency to store files in their own proprietary databases, hidden away in the system. I’m talking about iPhoto with its offsprings, and a few others. I can’t stand it. I need files to be left alone, in my specific personal folders. I want to be free to switch operating system if push comes to shove, so they need to be where I can intimately know and control the entire taxonomy. Full stop, no debates.</p>

<p>For exactly the same reason, I’ve long refused to use software forcing me to use their stupid cloud. Things like Apple Notes, among others.</p>

<details class="highlight">
<summary>On syncing files with smartphones</summary>
<p>To reiterate: I don't care about how "convenient" having files in perfect sync with a smartphone might be. I don't write or edit my stuff on a phone, don't even want to. When I'm out, the last thing I need is yet another way to "be productive", which is idiotic lingo to justify a sub-par culture promoting work overload and perennial tech distractions. I enjoy my free time, thank you very much. For the rare times when I need something important on my phone, I use <a href="https://syncthing.net/">Syncthing</a> (even though the sync direction it's 99% phone to computer, more like a phone backup). How can people still blindly trust cloud networks owned by US-based corporations, in 2025, is beyond me.</p>
</details>

<p>iA Writer 1.5.2, released in 2014, is the Nirvana. It lacks the Library, which means I’m free to keep my files wherever I want, and use the program as a pure editor, as in “open the file with”, either from Finder or within the program itself. It also means that it doesn’t need to load databases of sorts, so it opens in the blink of an eye.</p>

<p>Compatible with Mavericks, the application can open <code>.txt</code> files, obviously Markdown, and — drum roll — modern <code>.docx</code> documents for reasons that I have not yet investigated. It’s so good that I set it as default for all plain text formats, bypassing Text Edit. It lacks the dual panel for a preview, but with <code>CMD R</code>, I can summon it in a millisecond.</p>

<p>Finally, for the nerd corner, I like the Nitti font way more than their new IBM Plex Mono flavours.</p>

<h2 id="relationship-with-software-companies">Relationship with Software Companies</h2>

<p>Whenever I was unable to find an old compatible software version, I reached out to their makers. Except for <a href="https://www.alfredapp.com/">Alfred</a>, they were all in the audio field.</p>

<h3 id="alfred">Alfred</h3>

<p>I owned every version of Alfred except for v3. The lovely people at Running with Crayons Ltd (makers of Alfred) went above and beyond to help me out, offering an old legit licence for v3.</p>

<p>I thought that would be an exception: they’re a small company, based here in Cambridge, it won’t happen again…</p>

<h3 id="izotope">iZotope</h3>

<p>Next, there was <a href="https://www.izotope.com/">iZotope</a> — not a small company anymore — because of iDrum. iDrum was a drum machine that I’d purchased, as a boxed CD, in the early 2000s. My legit serial number was glued to the box, which I lost.</p>

<p>iZotope acquired <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dOChEQDTApY">iDrum</a> from its creator Art Gillespie in 2006, but for whatever reason, the licence never showed up in my iZotope account. Of course, the fact that it ceased to work on modern OSes didn’t help with finding out the discrepancy. It was a bygone product that I’d forgotten about.</p>

<p>Until I remembered it. Sent a ticket to support, hoping I wouldn’t get laughed at. Their quick response stunned me:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Lars (iZotope)</p>

  <p>Hello,</p>

  <p>below is a link and a serial number for idrum please try those.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Followed by a brand new legit serial number, and two links to download the last version of iDrum, one for Mac one for Windows. After I thanked them, I even received this follow-up:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>enjoy and happy creating!</p>

  <p>Sincerely,<br />
Lars</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Galvanised by this unexpected success, I reached out to each and every software company producing audio plug-ins that I know and use, asking for older versions that were not available on their websites.</p>

<p>Spoiler: I <strong>got them all</strong>.</p>

<h3 id="voxengo">Voxengo</h3>

<p><a href="https://www.voxengo.com/">Voxengo</a>’s CEO replied to me directly:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Hi! Since old versions are being requested very rarely, we handle them on case-by-case basis. Here is SPAN Plus 1.5 which should be compatible with MacOS 10.9: [link to follow]</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Again, I’ve no idea if I would miss new functionalities by using these old versions: I tried to load sessions that had SPAN Plus in the mix, and none have given me issues or weird sounding oddities.</p>

<h3 id="mcdsp">McDSP</h3>

<p>McDSP designs and develops the renowned <a href="https://mcdsp.com/plugin-index/compressor-bank/">Compressor Bank</a>, which I purchased a few years ago. They use iLok, and my v6 version is not compatible with Mavericks. I tried installing v5, but of course it fails to authorise because that’s how iLok works.</p>

<p>I wrote to them explaining my experiment, and this is what I got back:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Hello Simone,</p>

  <p>Thanks for reaching out about getting CompressorBank to work on your OSX Mavericks System.</p>

  <p>Since you are a owner of a perpetual v6 license, I have deposited you a perpetual Native v5 license for you to activate!</p>

  <p>You can activate your new license using the following instructions: [instructions here]</p>
</blockquote>

<p>That was amazing! They weren’t obliged at all, yet they were keen to help. I loved this.</p>

<h3 id="waves">Waves</h3>

<p>I left Waves for last, because a little voice inside my head insisted that they would have tried their best to avoid helping me out. I couldn’t have been more wrong. They were super helpful, sending very detailed instructions on how to install my compatible plug-ins and have them working on Mavericks.</p>

<p>It worked like a charm.</p>

<h3 id="others">Others</h3>

<p>Anyone else fell into either of these categories:</p>

<ul>
  <li>The software, even the newest release, is perfectly compatible with Mavericks (example: XLN Audio). I’m still happily surprised about this.</li>
  <li>Older versions were listed in plain sight on the dev’s website.</li>
  <li>Someone created a project to keep the latest versions running in older incompatible OSes, like <a href="https://github.com/i3roly/firefox-dynasty">Firefox Dinasty</a> and <a href="https://github.com/blueboxd/chromium-legacy">Chromium Legacy</a>.</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="apple">Apple</h3>

<p>I logged in to the App Store to see whether I could re-download old software purchased years ago… Yes, I could! That’s how I got ReadKit v2.4.6 (brilliant and beautiful RSS reader), Paste v1.1.3, and a few others.</p>

<p>I could have downloaded a compatible version of Pages, Numbers and Keynote from there as well, however, I leaned on the older ‘09 version of the suite, still called “iWork”. It looks, feels and behaves way better. The version of Pages shipped with it was the cheapest and closest thing to InDesign/Quark Xpress that ever existed. It also perfectly opens modern <code>.docx</code> files — but not recent versions of <code>.pages</code> files, which says a lot about Apple.</p>

<p>I will soon create a separate page on this site, with a list of all the software that I use in Mavericks.</p>

<h2 id="mavericks-forever">Mavericks Forever</h2>

<p>A week after I’d decided to go all-in, I got a hint off Mastodon about a website called <a href="https://mavericksforever.com/">Mavericks Forever</a>. Although I was already deep into the project, with many programs already collected and installed, the website by “wowfunhappy” gave me a couple of important hints. Without those, I would not have used Apple Mail, or used custom standalone web apps in a Firefox framework, such as Google Maps, Bitwarden, Syncthing. Since he gave away a template to create custom ones, I now have Disroot webmail and XMPP chat in my Dock.</p>

<p>I even exchanged a couple emails with wowfunhappy. Lovely chap.</p>

<h2 id="conclusions-subjective-opinions">Conclusions: Subjective Opinions</h2>

<p>I’ve been periodically using increased contrast modes in modern macOS because I often feel fatigued by flat design, with its lack of depth and texture, and too bright (or too dark) interface. Increased contrast is ugly, hence the “periodically”. Found this quote about the UI of pre-Yosemite Mac OS X versions:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>The increase contrast option in modern macOS increases the contrast at the expense of making everything ugly. Aqua in OS X 10.9 and below are naturally designed with high contrast and tonal range in mind.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>And <strong>boom</strong>, as someone used to say during live in-person keynotes. That’s it, in a nutshell. Using Mavericks for two months now, I’ve never felt the need to alter its GUI. Not once. Dark mode? Who cares. Transparency? When used with style, and plenty of usability testing before a release, it doesn’t hurt. It looks good.</p>

<p>Which brings me to the question of the lead designer. I believe Apple should have made Scott Forstall CEO instead of Timothy Donald Cook (that’s his full name, btw). Instead, <a href="https://www.businessinsider.com/ex-employee-why-firing-scott-forstall-was-a-mistake-2012-11">they fired him</a> after Jobs passed away, putting Jonathan Ive at the helm. Later, someone else <a href="https://lmnt.me/blog/a-responsibility-to-the-industry.html">became lead designer</a> after Ive left to join the AI craze.</p>

<p>The result? Apple ended up with trillions in the bank, and zero vision, selling unrepairable metal and glass slabs. A bland uninspiring luxury brand mostly aimed at rich privileged people, who I assume care very little for the environment, happy to live in an ad-hoc designed digital jail. Those, I don’t understand.</p>

<p>The “rest of us”, the probably still privileged but not-so-rich ones who still use old Apple products, are the people who keep using their hard-won devices, maintaining them because they’re fully aware of the value of money, because they see clearly when someone forces planned obsolescence down their throat. These, I understand.</p>

          <hr /><p><a href="mailto:hello@minutestomidnight.co.uk?subject=Getting%20Ready%20for%20the%20Winter.%20Part%201,%20Switching%20Technology">Reply via email</a></p>]]>
        </description>
        <pubDate>Thu, 18 Sep 2025 22:45:41 +0100</pubDate>
        <link>https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/getting-ready-for-the-winter-part-1/</link>
        <guid isPermaLink="false">https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/getting-ready-for-the-winter-part-1/</guid>
        <category>Personal</category>
        <category>Technology</category>
      </item>
      <item>
        <title>Settling</title>
        <author>hello@minutestomidnight.co.uk (Simone Silvestroni)</author>
        <description><![CDATA[
          
          <p>Enough with <a href="https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/tinnitus/">the whining</a>. Silvia and I have decided to kickstart the process that will ultimately lead us to share a dual citizenship. We came back to the UK two years ago, after failing to find common ground with our home country, and settled in our former house once again. Not coincidentally, we managed to find a way to pivot away from our old jobs.</p>

<p>None of the above was an easy feat, according to Westerner standards. It took time, and a great deal of effort.</p>

<p>Now, it would be possible (and easy) to speak at length about the problems of our adopted country. I would say that, at this age, my main interest is to focus on what I feel a keenship with, rather than the opposite.</p>

<p>We played that ill-fated game already, after the Brexit vote, for four years. It wiped us out. Then, Covid broke us, in every possible way, while we were exploring the possibility of migrating to Scandinavia between 2019 and the beginning of 2020. So, experiencing positive feelings about the place we’re living in is way more uplifting and motivating right now.</p>

<p>Also, what could people say to convince me not to get naturalised as a British citizen? Impending fascism? Sorry mate, our home country has already gone there three years ago — after having invented and tragically put to practice the goddamn concept 103 years ago.</p>

<p>There might be a “perfect” place somewhere else, for everyone. This might not be it, but we played our cards, and by accepting the hand we were dealt, we also take responsibility. For example, once we’re officially citizens, there’ll be two more votes that won’t go to fascists.</p>

          <hr /><p><a href="mailto:hello@minutestomidnight.co.uk?subject=Settling">Reply via email</a></p>]]>
        </description>
        <pubDate>Sun, 14 Sep 2025 16:09:54 +0100</pubDate>
        <link>https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/settling/</link>
        <guid isPermaLink="false">https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/settling/</guid>
        <category>Personal</category>
      </item>
      <item>
        <title>Tinnitus</title>
        <author>hello@minutestomidnight.co.uk (Simone Silvestroni)</author>
        <description><![CDATA[
          
          <p>Once again, I find myself kind of forced to stop reading the news, in any form or shape. Filtering shit from the interesting bits is like trying to put a barrier to a fastidious tinnitus (which I have, by the way).</p>

<p>After a long time applying a harsh set of filters on Mastodon, where anything caught in my extensive amount of ‘cancelled’ keywords would simply disappear, I tried showing the ‘filtered’ notification for a while. It only led to the trap of clicking, seeing things that I didn’t want to see.</p>

<p>So, back to erasing anything from this increasingly repulsive timeline I’m living in. Apparently, some guy that I’ve never heard of was murdered in another country, and for reasons that look a tad forced to me it’s been debated for days on end, even here. I’m seeing major newspapers, including the ones presenting themselves as ‘serious’ or ‘balanced’, giving a ton of space and emphasis to people mourning the one who was shot dead — in a country where gorillas could legally purchase a weapon, were they capable of learning to speak a dozen words — even though the victim was clearly an extremist nutcase.</p>

<p>I’m not advocating for shooting people, but when I was younger, even before the Berlin wall came down, such a case would have been mostly surrounded by silence, or at best relegated to a small article at page 7 of a regional newspaper. Why? Because someone who declares the things that the guy openly said across the years cannot be dignified with a debate. Fascists and their accolites can not be talked with, it’s in the definition. End of.</p>

<p>So yeah, I’m shutting down newspapers, a ton of keywords and more on Mastodon. Would I be exposed to tech discussions only? Not a problem. My main source of reading are my RSS software and a Kobo anyway. I’m sure I’ll be more or less up to date with the current absolute shit show that’s going on in the UK. However, the noise has surpassed the threshold of something even remotely meaningful.</p>

<p>Give me back Jack Kennedy and Nikita Khrushchev, I’d take it.</p>

          <hr /><p><a href="mailto:hello@minutestomidnight.co.uk?subject=Tinnitus">Reply via email</a></p>]]>
        </description>
        <pubDate>Sun, 14 Sep 2025 14:42:58 +0100</pubDate>
        <link>https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/tinnitus/</link>
