      </item>
      <item>
        <title>So Be It</title>
        <author>hello@minutestomidnight.co.uk (Simone Silvestroni)</author>
        <description><![CDATA[
          A year and three months later, a follow-up on <a href='/blog/leaving-the-web-industry/'>leaving the web industry</a>. I was supposed to have distanced myself from that by now, to speak about it lightly. Not true.
          <p class="highlight"><strong>Disclaimer</strong>: most of the content for this article comes from a few posts of mine published between 2013 and 2014 on the blog of my then co-directed web design/dev London-based firm. Sometimes things don’t change.</p>

<p>Applying to jobs bearing the title ‘Front-end Developer’ never landed well with me. Seeing how I never accepted the demise of <em>web designer</em>, the imposed division between developers and “UX designers” felt like the fruit of a narrow-minded vision. Without any doubt, it was a large contributor to the multiplication of horrible and unusable web products. As a designer who can code, with an extensive experience, I used to be comfortable in being present at each stage of a web production.</p>

<p>After spending more than two decades working for all kind of clients, building a familiarity with how browsers behave, developing a knack for making simple concepts shine, honing a natural ability to discern the best typography for each situation, I could achieve what I consider a good web design:</p>

<ol>
  <li>Creating websites that worked well on any browser, maintaining a visual consistency without obsessing over every cross-platform minute differences.</li>
  <li>Coding with web standards for sustainability, durability, and maintainability.</li>
  <li>Learning WCAG guidelines and ARIA roles enough to make them accessible to everyone.</li>
  <li>Staying away from pointless buzzwords, such as “pixel-perfect”, “above the fold” or any other soundbites constantly regurgitated by every recruiter in the industry — and probably by “AI” now.</li>
  <li>Relentlessly testing my work against the proper validators.</li>
</ol>

<p>Working with the largest clients made me realise what people want, but especially with what they <em>don’t want</em>. That is why I addressed accessibility and performance from the get-go, instead of an afterthought.</p>

<h2 id="reinventing-the-wheel">Reinventing the wheel</h2>

<p>I’ve witnessed many tech fads throughout my career, especially web frameworks, with their cycle of time and energy wasted to learn the stack, only to see it slowly morphing into something different, or simply cease to exist. One recent example being JAMstack, which I kind of welcomed a while ago, before realising that it even had the JAM acronym upside down: familiarity with progressive enhancement would make it evident that Markup should come before APIs, with Javascript as a last step to add interaction, when and if needed. I get it: MAJ would not have given a VC-funded Silicon Valley startup a funky name to extract enough money.</p>

<p>Ironically, while each and every framework shared the same theoretical goal of stop reinventing the wheel, it ended up in a deathly spiral of doing precisely that: reinventing the wheel by using different names and architectural starting points.</p>

<p>I used to be baffled as to why the web industry kept behaving this way, shifting from one fragile cauldron to the next, creating unmaintainable cathedrals on quicksand while trying to reach El Dorado: the ultimate vendor lock-in. With all that’s been happening over the last few years of late-stage capitalism, I now understand <em>why</em>.</p>

<p>Yet, I’ve always preferred to create my design and code ‘system’ — modular, easy to apply and adaptable, based on a solid foundation of accessibility, usability, performance. My work did NOT need Javascript or any progressive enhancement, because it should have been the foundation. Other people were supposed to improve on that, using progressive enhancement if required.</p>

<p>Does this mean that I’m out of the game in today’s upside-down web industry? So be it. Happy to have pivoted out of it. Sitting by the river, watching the dead results passing by: a web full of crap, slow, inaccessibile, fragile, broken. Good riddance. Enjoy your JS-only designers, and the way nobody notices the oxymoron.</p>

<p>My tech stack was made of solid semantic HTML, even when created by either PHP or a static site generator (the Liquid template language, for example), and well-structured CSS. Jeremy Keith said, <a href="https://adactio.com/journal/12571"><em>CSS is simple but not easy</em></a>, which is why developers who are not familiar with web standards always fail.</p>

<p>Someone wrote this on their blog — and I’m royally pissed that I didn’t take note of the name, or the URL:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>CSS frameworks such as Bootstrap or Tailwind might be a good way to quickly work on prototypes, but they hinder knowledge of CSS. Using them as the foundation for a workflow is the telltale sign of developers who don’t know how to properly approach design and web standards. Web design takes time, care, and proper testing. Trusting frameworks to do the heavy lifting is part of what make websites unusable and inaccessible today.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Hopefully, I’ll find out the source one day.</p>

<hr aria="" role="hidden" />

<p>Similar and related concepts are talked about in these articles:</p>

<ul>
  <li><a href="https://heather-buchel.com/blog/2023/10/why-your-web-design-sucks/">It’s 2023, here is why your web design sucks</a>, by Heather Buchel.</li>
  <li><a href="https://thoughtbot.com/blog/tailwind-and-the-femininity-of-css">Tailwind and the Femininity of CSS</a>, by Elaina Natario.</li>
  <li><a href="https://nuejs.org/blog/tailwind-misinformation-engine/">Tailwind marketing and misinformation engine</a>, by Tero Piirainen.</li>
</ul>

          <hr /><p><a href="mailto:hello@minutestomidnight.co.uk?subject=So%20Be%20It">Reply via email</a></p>]]>
        </description>
        <pubDate>Tue, 09 Sep 2025 17:02:05 +0100</pubDate>
        <link>https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/so-be-it/</link>
        <guid isPermaLink="false">https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/so-be-it/</guid>
        <category>Personal</category>
        <category>Technology</category>
      </item>
      <item>
        <title>Acceptance</title>
        <author>hello@minutestomidnight.co.uk (Simone Silvestroni)</author>
        <description><![CDATA[
          Six months ago, I offered to produce, mix, and master the debut album for a friend. One out of several good reasons to do so was selfish: use their project to complete a process of re-igniting my music production workflow, and rekindle with all the intrinsic mechanisms that are needed for a quality delivery. A process that I had successfully started with <a href='/blog/la-matiere-meme-du-temps/'>Zavajer at the end of last year</a>.
          <p>The idea was to start offering sound production services again, as a side activity. I didn’t think that through. Taking six months for a 6-song album uncovered an obvious problem, especially if compared to how, back in the day, it used to take less than three weeks, including all the back-and-forth with the author, and proper quality testing.</p>

<p>I can go on however I want to find reasons as to why it took me so long, but it boils down to a simple linear truth: I don’t want to do it. Having a day job means that I can only use a few hours here and there, or the weekend, or my holidays, to work on music production. Reality showed me that it’s my free time, time to do personal stuff, enjoy relationships, go visit places, do house chores, et cetera.</p>

<p>Having said that, I’m proud of the album, no matter how my obsessed mind will always consider my work as sub-par. Obsessed by a past standard that’s currently unattainable to me, that I used to achieve because I poured ten hours a day into the craft, every day, for years. Yet, the simple fact of being proud of this new production is a giant step for me. It means starting to accept that perfection is not of this world, and that sometimes <em>good enough</em> is the best for everyone.</p>

<p>A fulfilling explanation of how things are with me and music production came out of a nice discussion with another friend and musician, with whom I’ve been collaborating for almost ten years. We share the same age and a similar living situation, so we found each other agreeing with wanting to savour our free time in peace, without obsessing over having to perform something else at any cost.</p>

<p>We also shared the logical result of the above: turn our focus on our music instead. Having no deadline, whatever and whenever it comes to us, work on new music to keep the flame going. Do we have something to say, something to play? Let’s record that, and produce the outcome at our pace.</p>

<p>Acceptance is sometimes hard, but when it comes it’s satisfying.</p>

          <hr /><p><a href="mailto:hello@minutestomidnight.co.uk?subject=Acceptance">Reply via email</a></p>]]>
        </description>
        <pubDate>Mon, 08 Sep 2025 11:55:23 +0100</pubDate>
        <link>https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/acceptance/</link>
        <guid isPermaLink="false">https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/acceptance/</guid>
        <category>Personal</category>
        <category>Music</category>
      </item>
      <item>
        <title>Looking for a niche</title>
        <author>hello@minutestomidnight.co.uk (Simone Silvestroni)</author>
        <description><![CDATA[
          <a href='/blog/nostalgia/'>Adding some flare back</a> to the current uninspiring design of Mac OS wasn't enough. After spending a day using an old Mac running Mavericks, I realised how I probably need to find a tiny place somewhere in the past.
          <p>A certainty formed after a couple of hours playing with my recently acquired 2013 MacBook Air. I hadn’t seen Mac OS X 10.9.5 — the last OS Apple released before deciding to move everything to a flat, boring, and often confusing interface — for more than a decade, and I must say it: it was GUI peak design.</p>

<p>Even though the laptop has only 4 gigs of RAM, I managed to easily install and run Logic Studio 2.1, which included Logic Pro 9.1.8, Soundtrack, Waveburner, and the whole 50-ish GB pro sound package. Then, installing Adobe Creative Suite 4, which looks and behaves great, confirmed a fact: nothing added to later iterations of the software was actually needed — at least from my point of view.</p>

<p>The fact that everything is so incredibly fast and smooth leaves me speechless. To think that I got this machine for free only to have a play with my beloved old Logic Pro 9, it’s now showing how the fenomenon called <em>retro computing</em> has a more meaningful and deep outcome than I previously believed.</p>

<figure class="fullscreen">
	<img src="https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/assets/images/mavericks-logicstudio-installation.webp" alt="Screenshot of Logic Studio 2 installer in Mac OS X Mavericks" width="1440" height="900" />
	<figcaption>Installing Logic Studio 2</figcaption>
</figure>

<p>Everything I do on that computer feels like magic somehow. Animations are unobtrusive and perfectly calibrated, the depth of the UI design is very satisfying to the eyes, while interacting with every system component feels quick, intuitive, natural. Even the system typography looks soothing and more readable. Working with Finder results in more clarity compared to any flat design alternative that followed.</p>

<p>Launching Logic and the rest of the audio suite was both a pleasure and a series of why. Why did they have to dumb down everything? The so-called Apple Pro Apps from the Jobs era were amazing, efficient, and easy to use for skilled professionals. The difference between Logic and Garage Band was remarkable, but it had meaning. Same for Final Cut and iMovie: conflating the two to a minimum low denominator, presumably to appease the masses, was absolutely detrimental.</p>

<p>One day I shoud properly analyse why Logic Pro X has always been giving me eye fatigue, while the previous version 9 never did.</p>

<figure class="fullscreen">
	<img src="https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/assets/images/mavericks-logicpro-9.webp" alt="Screenshot of Logic Pro 9.1.8 showing the demo song" width="1440" height="900" />
	<figcaption>Logic Pro 9.1.8</figcaption>
</figure>

<p>Another idiocy that I’ve never forgiven Apple for, was the decision to discontinue Soundtrack Pro. I suppose it followed the same path as Aperture, beloved by many photographers: dumbing down everything to conflate a ‘pro’ line to consumer level — Photos.app in this latter example.</p>

<p>Soundtrack Pro, which featured a dual mode (multitrack and single track audio editor), was an absolute favourite during my sound design years. It was never replaced.</p>

<figure class="fullscreen">
	<img src="https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/assets/images/mavericks-soundtrack-audio-editor.webp" alt="Screenshot of Soundtrack Pro in single audio track edit mode" width="1440" height="900" />
	<figcaption>Soundtrack Pro, single track mode</figcaption>
</figure>

<figure class="fullscreen">
	<img src="https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/assets/images/mavericks-soundtrack-multitrack.webp" alt="Screenshot of Soundtrack Pro in multitrack mode" width="1440" height="900" />
	<figcaption>Soundtrack Pro, multitrack mode</figcaption>
</figure>

<h2 id="back-in-time">Back in time</h2>

<p>After my latest two posts, adding whimsical flare to the flat macOS was not enough for me. I had a look at old OS versions before Apple completely lost the plot with Big Sur, and noticed how, up until Catalina, Finder windows still had gradients and depth. Clarity was at least still in part present.</p>

<p>So, of course I went back to Catalina (10.15.7) on my daily drive. Catalina received its last security patch 2 years ago. I don’t really care. I keep the WiFi off for most of my day anyway, I run Little Snitch and a firewall, I’m not worried.</p>

<p>What has the Mavericks experiment showed me? That I grew up in a world where designers cared about their work, and also about the people who would end up using such work. Also, it demonstrated, in a direct and somehow brutal way, how every single so-called improvement that came later was mostly redundant, likely a marketing gimmick forced to sell more crap.</p>

<p>While I started the experiment for a single reason: creating and producing a single song on Logic 9 to prove that music gear is secondary to creativity, I might end up looking for a powerful old Mac hardware where I can run Mac OS X 10.9.5 and use software from 15 years ago for all my activities. Most of it is considered abandonware, but it still works better than any new incarnation, and it can export to the same universal formats.</p>

<p>I fear that, faced with the current shit show in the tech world, going back is the only sane way to survive.</p>

          <hr /><p><a href="mailto:hello@minutestomidnight.co.uk?subject=Looking%20for%20a%20niche">Reply via email</a></p>]]>
        </description>
        <pubDate>Sun, 27 Jul 2025 21:14:09 +0100</pubDate>
        <link>https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/looking-for-a-niche/</link>
        <guid isPermaLink="false">https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/looking-for-a-niche/</guid>
        <category>Personal</category>
        <category>Technology</category>
      </item>
      <item>
        <title>Nostalgia</title>
        <author>hello@minutestomidnight.co.uk (Simone Silvestroni)</author>
        <description><![CDATA[
          Over the last ten years or so, a dominant theme has been nostalgia. While initially convinced it was strictly related to my personal struggle with ageing, I've now changed my mind.
          <p>A constant in my journal, a constant in other people’s blogs and posts on the Fediverse, the accompanying creeping malaise doesn’t seem to only affect Gen Xers and their process of getting old. It’s everywhere, online, offline, in personal conversations, in magazine essays, books, podcasts. It’s like every facet of our present has been touched by some dystopian Midas king, who turns everything to shit.</p>

<p>Apple, once a rebel outcast of sorts, has become the dark menacing big brother from their famous 1984 Macintosh ad. Google’s founding motto, <em>Don’t be evil</em>, is so obviously an oxymoron by now that they’ve removed it from everywhere.</p>

<p>The internet, once a safe exciting place for creativity, exchange, discovery and personal growth, is now a gigantic commercial jail, an over-complex intricate web of honey pots built for surveillance and exploitation.</p>

<p>What appear to be the last embers of capitalism have extended their grasp on everything, online and offline, taking control of people’s choices, language, thoughts, and especially wallets. The image of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/quotes/139439-there-will-be-no-curiosity-no-enjoyment-of-the-process">a boot stamping on a human face forever</a> comes to mind. Only, as I keep saying, we’re not in Orwellian territory here — that would have been too transparent for capitalism. We’re in <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Brave-New-World">Huxley territory</a>. This is a twisted version of <em>Brand New World</em>.</p>

<p>Masses have accepted a crippling addiction to modern crap technology as if it’s normal. Technology that’s built — on purpose or not — to be devoid of any attempt of aiding spontaneous human interactions. Nothing is maintainable, nor built to last. It needs to be disposable in the worst possible consumeristic sense: constantly replaced, year after year, by the next “best” version of itself.</p>

<p>Huxley used the concept of Ford’s assembly line as the metaphor for dispotic efficiency. Isn’t the cult of productivity today revered and relentlessly <a href="https://brainbaking.com/post/2023/03/continuous-productivity-is-toxic/">pushed down everyone’s throat</a> as a way to achieve wealth, success and ultimately power?</p>

<p>I was truly speechless when I saw the latest Apple’s pretentious and hollow staged presentation at WWDC. It felt like it had reached its dystopian nadir when the horrifying AI vocal assistant spewed fake praises and platitudes in a person’s headset after a run. Realising how they shot the scene without an inch of irony left me stunned. No episode of <em>Black Mirror</em> ever hit me with such strength: at least I’d know it’s a work of fantasy, while this shit is real.</p>

<p>The internet as I knew it from 1995 to 2005 is probably mostly gone, barely saved by these tiny pouches of niche writers, who keep posting on their personal sites, trying to stay afloat among oceans of SEO scams, ads, tracking, data leaks, and the constant siphoning of personal data. Let’s not dive into “social” media giants, carelessly involved in genocides and political jerrymandering on each side of the Atlantic and beyond.</p>

<p>And then, the crushing push of standardisation everywhere. Design isn’t a creative field anymore, let’s not fool ourselves. Except the above niche of stubborn individuals, and little communities here and there, everything has been flattened and homogenised. 95% of all the websites I’ve seen over the last decade is a cookie-cut template, spawned out of one of a million overcomplicated frameworks out there, built to constantly reinvent the wheel and destroy the very fabric of what made the web interesting and fun.</p>

<p>Over the last couple days I stumbled upon a few examples.</p>

<h2 id="web-design">Web Design</h2>

<p>Like many of my peers, I vividly remember when the world of web design was turned upside down by a collective who campaigned to stop the so-called browser wars, to impose web standards over the drift of software giants’ proprietary crap. They called themselves <em>The Web Standards Project</em>. From their last blog post:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>When The Web Standards Project (WaSP) formed in 1998, the web was the battleground in an ever-escalating war between two browser makers—Netscape and Microsoft—who were each taking turns “advancing” HTML to the point of collapse. You see, in an effort to one-up each other, the two browsers introduced new elements and new ways of manipulating web documents; this escalated to the point where their respective 4.0 versions were largely incompatible.<cite><a href="https://www.webstandards.org/2013/03/01/our-work-here-is-done/index.html">Aaron Gustafson</a></cite></p>
</blockquote>

<p>Back then, together with <a href="https://silviamaggidesign.com">Silvia</a> and a few friends and colleagues, I started to apply strict rules of usability and accessibility to my work, making large use of web standards and guidelines. A source of constant inspiration was <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeffrey_Zeldman">Jeffrey Zeldman</a>. His books, along with the websites he designed or contributed to design, were at the forefront of my learning process. I loved his style, liked the things he wrote, and followed his example.</p>

<p>This is Zeldman’s homepage in 2005:</p>

<p class="fullscreen"><img src="https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/assets/images/jeffrey-zeldman-presents-the-daily-report-2005.webp" alt="The Daily Report, screenshot from the Web Archive" width="1942" height="1582"></p>

<p>Over the last 6 years, Zeldman’s website used one of the default WordPress themes, <a href="https://wordpress.org/documentation/article/twenty-twenty/">Twenty Twenty</a>, a cookie-cut template. Apparently, he’s been working on a custom redesign, which is almost ready to go online. My point is that he stopped being an example, and decided to adapt to the flat homogenised world of modular scalable anonymous nothingness.</p>

<p>Out of transparency: I too used Twenty Twenty for a few months when it came out, quickly getting tired of it due to a simple fact: it didn’t feel mine.</p>

<p>The personal consequence of gutting the web of creativity, personal flare and diversity is simple: I now only enjoy small websites, part of what is commonly called small (or Indie) web. Anything else goes straight to my RSS reader, or gets ignored.</p>

<h2 id="music-concerts">Music Concerts</h2>

<p>A week ago, Live Aid has reached its 40th anniversary. Silvia and I have been watching sets from the various places (Wembley, Philadelphia) and something suddenly hit me. The stage was neither small nor gigantic, with a very simple set up: a white static background showing the iconic guitar-shaped Africa silhouette, a static banner saying ‘FEED THE WORLD - July 13th 1985 at WEMBLEY STADIUM’, again the logo over the left and right speakers, and nothing else. Maybe a couple sponsors here and there, Pepsi being among them, but nothing really overwhelming.</p>

<p class="fullscreen"><img src="https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/assets/images/live-aid.webp" alt="Photo of the stage at Wembley stadium while David Bowie performs live" width="615" height="433"></p>

<p>On stage, high quality acts performed everything live: no autotune, no pre-recorded crap. Everything kept simple and real. Artists looking spontaneous, happy to improvise and stretch their songs longer than the canonical three minutes. Normal and fun clothes, no pretentious gigantic dancing crews or pointless laser shows. Then, from the stage it’s easy to observe the massive crowds: how happy they were, just by being there and enjoy the shows. They moved their arms left and right, clapped on beat, sang. No lights from phone torches, no time wasted taking crap videos or selfies. They were there, <em>committed to the moment</em>.</p>

<p>The personal consequence of how things have changed is that I completely avoid going to live gigs. The last time I truly enjoyed a concert in person was more than ten years ago. Mike Peters of the Alarm, in a London club. Might have been because the crowd was full of Gen X like me, but nobody had a mobile phone in their hands, and everyone sang with Mike.</p>

<h2 id="os-interfaces">OS Interfaces</h2>

<p>As I wrote abundantly over the last few years, I jumped across operating systems and platforms, looking for something that does not exist, at least for me. What did I notice? When Microsoft changed its design to a flat aesthetic, and sadly Apple followed suit with iOS 7 and Mac OS Yosemite, everyone else jumped on board.</p>

<p>Just look at this simple example. iOS logos across time:</p>

<p><img src="https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/assets/images/ios-involution.webp" alt="All iOS version logos from 1 to 14, 2007-2020" width="1440" height="1440"></p>

<p>Easy to spot the watershed moment: the first six iterations had their own personality and a distinct look, while the following versions simply drown in the indistinguishable minimalistic cookie-cut approach.</p>

<p>Everything is now flat; depth, shadows and gradients have been removed, along with the ability to easily use the interface to navigate a system. Readability seems unimportant, accessibility a second thought. Even a large part of desktop environments in Linux decided to go with this flow. Zorin OS’ bright interface is blinding to me, while its dark mode unnervingly hard to use, and this is a mere example.</p>

<p>Then, a few weeks ago, I installed Mac OS X 10.9 ‘Mavericks’ on an old 2010 MacBook Air. Two things immediately stood out: depth, gradients, shadows, real buttons, real links, were all incredibly easier to spot and use properly. Readability massively better across the system, along with a feeling of being treated like a normal person. Instead of imposing a flat uninspiring interface, only to dumb down everything else in order to help people using their crap, Apple used to be way less patronising. During installation, I was never presented with the ridiculous choice “Yes/Maybe later” — instead, they asked a question, offering a yes/no possibility. How refreshing!</p>

<p>Silvia and I have been reading a lot of <a href="https://lmnt.me/blog/rose-gold-tinted-liquid-glasses.html">Louie Mantia</a> lately. I knew him from his past work, and used to have his icons back in the day. Louie’s latest rants truly resonated with us, prompting a decision to restore some whimsicality to our Macs. I have now <a href="https://apps.apple.com/us/app/lickable-menu-bar/id6444217677?mt=12">an Aqua look</a> for my menu bar:</p>

<p><img src="https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/assets/images/lickable-menu.webp" alt="Screenshot of the left side of my Mac OS menu bar" width="964" height="214"></p>

<p>Used <a href="https://www.macenhance.com/iconchamp.html">Icon Champ</a> to replace the default flat icons with past versions or their current actual logos, without the rounded square constraint that looks so innatural on Mac:</p>

<p><img src="https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/assets/images/system-apps.webp" alt="Screenshot of the application Icon Champ showing a list of customised icons" width="2166" height="1646"></p>

<p>Used Louie’s ‘Forstall folders’ <a href="https://lmnt.me/blog/icons/">icon sets</a> to make my Finder fun to look at:</p>

<p><img src="https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/assets/images/home.webp" alt="Screenshot of my home folder showing custom purple icons" width="1690" height="960"></p>

<p>Turned my Monterey’s horrible Dock into something lively:</p>

<p><img src="https://minutestomidnight.co.uk/assets/images/dock.webp" alt="Screenshot of my Dock showing custom irregular icons" width="1472" height="212"></p>

<h2 id="conclusions">Conclusions</h2>

<p>Maybe it’s just nostalgia, but I have a strong feeling that a series of interconnected bad decisions are responsible for something that has turned almost everything to a worse version of itself.</p>

<p>I’ll leave with another of Louie’s observations:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>For all of this to be largely dictated by a person who has little-to-no support amongst industry experts? I frankly can’t believe it. No one I know would ask Alan Dye to design their app. Adopting Liquid Glass is no different. Why would anyone subscribe to a design system created by a person you don’t consider to be a good designer? <cite>Louie Mantia, <a href="https://lmnt.me/blog/a-responsibility-to-the-industry.html">A Responsibility to the Industry</a></cite></p>
</blockquote>

          <hr /><p><a href="mailto:hello@minutestomidnight.co.uk?subject=Nostalgia">Reply via email</a></p>]]>
